> Not to be confused with rice, orzo is actually a type of pasta. Whilst chorizo gives some of the flavour, we're also using smoky base paste, made with smoked paprika and smoked salt, to bring rich smoky flavour to your dish.

Boil a full #kettle{}. 

Pour the boiled @water{1.5%liters} into a #saucepan{} with @salt{1/2%tsp} and bring back to the boil.

When boiling, add the @orzo{180%grams} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{10%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @olive oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{90%grams} and fry until it starts to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

While the chorizo fries, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Add the garlic, @Central American Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and @tomato puree{30%grams} to the chorizo.

Fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @creme fraiche{75%grams}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the sauce{150%ml} into the chorizo and bring to a boil.

Reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%grams}, @peas{120%grams} and @smoky base paste{1%sachet} through the sauce until the cheese has melted. Drain the @burrata{125%grams}, then carefully halve it.

Once melted, stir the cooked orzo through the sauce.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

Share the smoky chorizo orzo between your #serving bowls{}.

Top with the burrata halves and @wild rocket{20%grams} leaves.

Finish by drizzling over the @balsamic glaze{12%ml}. Enjoy!